Practice Problems — Topic 1
Q1. Trace resistance calculation:
A 2oz copper (T=70µm) PCB trace on your flyback converter carries 5A continuous. Trace length = 30mm, width = 2mm. ρ_Cu at 80°C = 2.1×10⁻⁸ Ω·m.
(a) Cross-sectional area A = W × T
(b) DC resistance R = ρ×L/A
(c) Voltage drop V = I×R
(d) Power dissipated P = I²×R
(e) Temperature rise: using ΔT = P/(surface_area × h) where surface area = 2×(L×W) (top and bottom of trace) and h = 10 W/(m²·K) for natural convection. Is this acceptable (< 20°C rise)?
Q2. Parasitic inductance and its effect:
A switching loop (MOSFET + capacitor + diode) has traces totalling 25mm in length.
(a) Estimated loop inductance using 1nH/mm rule
(b) At turn-off with dI/dt = 100A/µs (10A switching off in 100ns): voltage spike V = L×dI/dt
(c) MOSFET rated 60V, V_in=24V: drain voltage during spike = V_in + V_spike. Does the MOSFET survive?
(d) If trace length is reduced to 8mm: recalculate spike. Does MOSFET survive now?
(e) This illustrates why minimising switching loop area is critical. Name two PCB layout techniques to minimise switching loop area.
Q3. Trace width design for a 12V, 8A buck converter:
Current-carrying paths: high-side MOSFET to inductor (I_rms = I_load×√D = 8×√0.5 = 5.66A), inductor to output capacitor (8A continuous), gate drive trace (peak 2A, short duration).
(a) Using IPC-2221 table, minimum width for 5.66A at 10°C rise, 2oz copper (divide table width by 1.4)
(b) Minimum width for 8A continuous at 20°C rise, 2oz copper
(c) Gate drive trace width (2A, short duration — use 0.5A RMS estimate): minimum width at 10°C rise
(d) What happens thermally if you use the minimum width from (b) for the 8A trace but copper is at 85°C ambient?
(e) For the 8A continuous output trace, would you use a routed trace or a copper pour? Justify.
Q4. PCB stack-up decision:
You are designing a 400W half-bridge converter PCB. Primary bus voltage 390V. Secondary output 12V/33A.
(a) Is a 2-layer or 4-layer PCB more appropriate? Give two specific reasons.
(b) For a 4-layer PCB, propose a layer stack-up. Which layer should be ground plane and why?
(c) The 33A secondary output trace needs what minimum width on 2oz copper? (Use IPC-2221 at 20°C rise — extrapolate from table)
(d) At 390V primary voltage, what is the minimum creepage distance between primary copper and secondary copper on the PCB? (Refer to Topic 1 of this month)
(e) The transformer sits at the boundary between primary and secondary. How do you handle the 6.4mm creepage requirement at the transformer mounting footprint on the PCB?
Q5. PCB specification exercise:
Write the complete manufacturing specification for your Year 1 flyback capstone PCB (30W, 230V mains input, 12V/2A output). Include:
(a) All standard manufacturing parameters (layers, thickness, copper weight, surface finish, soldermask)
(b) Minimum trace and space requirements
(c) Isolation requirement between primary and secondary copper
(d) Any special requirements for the high-voltage primary side (creepage slots, primary-to-secondary spacing)
(e) Estimated cost from an online PCB manufacturer for 5 prototype boards (research JLCPCB or PCBWay pricing for these specifications)
